{"by": "aterp", "id": 43182336, "parent": 43182152, "text": "I hear you, real Python has its benefits :) The way I see it, these are different approaches to solving similar (but still quite different) problems. In the case of rad, it&#x27;s just a language, it&#x27;s not trying to replace your shell, but the fact that it&#x27;s only Python-<i>like</i> might indeed deter some people. But - it also opens up some unique syntax that can be tailored really well to CLI scripts. For example, the syntax for args [1] or json &quot;rad blocks&quot; [2], as I&#x27;ve called them.<p>[1] <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;amterp.github.io&#x2F;rad&#x2F;guide&#x2F;args&#x2F;#arg-declarations\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;amterp.github.io&#x2F;rad&#x2F;guide&#x2F;args&#x2F;#arg-declarations</a><p>[2] <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;amterp.github.io&#x2F;rad&#x2F;guide&#x2F;rad-blocks&#x2F;#basic-example\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;amterp.github.io&#x2F;rad&#x2F;guide&#x2F;rad-blocks&#x2F;#basic-example</a>", "time": 1740563998, "type": "comment"}